To create a floating label for your input fields in a web application, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript or a CSS framework like Bootstrap or Material-UI  . Here's a simple implementation using HTML and CSS:

HTML:
```html
<div class="floating-label">
  <input type="text" id="input-text" class="floating-input" placeholder=" " required>
  <label for="input-text" class="floating-label">Your Label</label>
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.floating-label {
  position: relative;
}

.floating-input,
.floating-label {
  font-size: 16px;
  line-height: 24px;
}

.floating-input {
  display: block;
  padding: 8px 0;
  border: none;
  border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
  outline: none;
  transition: border-color 0.3s ease;
}

.floating-label {
  position: absolute;
  top: 16px;
  left: 0;
  pointer-events: none;
  color: #9b9b9b;
  transition: 0.3s ease top, 0.3s ease color;
}

.floating-input:focus,
.floating-input:not(:placeholder-shown) {
  border-color: #000;
}

.floating-input:focus + .floating-label,
.floating-input:not(:placeholder-shown) + .floating-label {
  top: -8px;
  color: #000;
}
```

This code creates a floating label effect by positioning the label absolutely within a relative container . When the input field is focused or has content, the label moves to the top and changes color . The transition property provides a smooth animation effect as the label transitions to the focused state .

An **in-memory database** is a database that resides entirely in the memory of the application and does not persist data on disk. It can be useful for testing purposes when you don't want to mock out a complete data access layer, or if you need to have a real database due to an ORM .

**Mock** is a technique that allows you to create fake objects that simulate the behavior of real objects in a controlled way. You can use mock objects to isolate the code under test from its dependencies and verify that the expected interactions occur.

To inject the in-memory database with mock and achieve the same results as your database, you need to do the following steps:

- Create a mock object for your database context using a mocking framework like Moq.
- Configure the mock object to return an in-memory database provider when the options property is accessed.
- Pass the mock object to the constructor of your class under test.
- Use the mock object to verify the expected calls to the database context methods.

Here is an example of how to do this using EF Core and Moq:

```csharp
// Arrange
var options = new DbContextOptionsBuilder<MyDbContext>()
    .UseInMemoryDatabase(databaseName: "TestDb")
    .Options;

var mockContext = new Mock<MyDbContext>(options);
mockContext.Setup(m => m.Foos).ReturnsDbSet(new List<Foo>());

var sut = new MyClassUnderTest(mockContext.Object);

// Act
sut.DoSomething();

// Assert
mockContext.Verify(m => m.SaveChanges(), Times.Once());
```

I hope this helps.

